Today, establishing internal corporate phone communication by purchasing separate phones for each employee of a company or institution is costly and illogical.
Local communication telephone systems, commonly referred to as PBX (Private Branch Exchange) or "Centrale," have the capability to provide as many extensions as you require.
This allows employees to communicate with their colleagues for free and enables them to share main phone lines among themselves. 
Among the most important features of this system is the Interactive Voice Response (IVR) system,
whereby if someone from outside the organization calls your numbers, after a welcome message, they are given the option to be connected to the desired department. 
A central telephone system (PBX) includes the following devices:

1.  Main Unit
2.  Operator Phone (Specialized Phone)
3.  Standard Extension Phone
4.  Terminal Box
